<Base
  title="HanGL · Surface Hangul, Latent Hanja · Xiaochuan Li"
  description="An empirical pilot: do multilingual LLMs ground Korean Sino-Korean words to a latent Hanja/Chinese meaning, or only to surface script? A causal wrong-Hanja intervention shows latent grounding is a function of model capability."
  showProgress={true}
  toc={true}
>
  <article class="prose">
    <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Application frontier · empirical pilot · real LLMs
    </div>
    <h1>HanGL — Surface Hangul, Latent Hanja</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      The structure-versus-surface question, run on real models through a natural phenomenon.
    </p>

    <p>
      This is the program's central question — <em>is a model's behaviour licensed by the genuine
      structure, or by a surface proxy that correlates with it?</em> — taken out of the
      <a href="/research/mini-causal-models">MiniCausalLang</a> sandbox and onto frontier LLMs, using
      a phenomenon that supplies an unusually clean separation between surface and structure for free.
    </p>

    <h2>Why Sino-Korean is a clean probe</h2>
    <p>
      Modern Korean is written in Hangul, but much of its vocabulary is <strong>Sino-Korean</strong> —
      words with a Hanja (Chinese-character) origin that is no longer written. The key property:
      Hangul and Hanja share <strong>zero character overlap</strong> (학교 vs. 學校 / 学校), yet
      correspond systematically in meaning. So if a model places 학교 near 学校 in representation
      space, that proximity <em>cannot</em> come from shared surface tokens — it can only come from a
      latent lexical-semantic structure. Most cross-lingual alignment work is confounded by subword
      overlap; here the confound is absent by construction. It is the same logic as the
      <a href="/research/sc-certification">grounding question</a>: fluent surface use is not evidence
      that the structure is load-bearing.
    </p>

    <h2>The result</h2>
    <HanGLFigure />
    <p>
      The probe brackets a <strong>correct</strong>, a <strong>wrong</strong>, or a
      <strong>placebo</strong> Hanja onto the Hangul word — a <code>do</code>-style intervention on the
      surface cue — and asks whether the model's answer follows the context or the cue. Two effects,
      measured across models from weak to strong, tell one story:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Hanja Gain</strong> — how much a <em>correct</em> Hanja helps. For every frontier model
        it is ≈ 0: they already resolve the word from Hangul alone, so the explicit cue is redundant.
        For a weak model (Qwen2.5-1.5B) it is <strong>+0.52</strong> — the Hanja triples its accuracy
        on rare words it does not otherwise know.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Wrong-Hanja Cost</strong> — how much a <em>wrong</em> Hanja misleads. No model is fully
        immune (all CIs exclude zero), but the weak model <strong>caves</strong> (+0.55, following the
        false cue 58% of the time) while strong models mostly hold (+0.09–0.21).
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      So <strong>latent Hanja grounding is a function of model capability</strong>: a strong model has
      internalised the structure — it neither needs the correct cue nor is led by a false one — while a
      weak model has not, and is both. Among frontier models, the Chinese-strong one relies on the
      surface cue the most.
    </p>

    <h2>Three layers, and a representational echo</h2>
    <p>
      The claim is carried by a behavioural probe (the figure above), a causal one (correct vs. wrong
      vs. placebo Hanja, isolating the cue's content from the bracket itself), and a representational
      one. The representational side measures Sino-Korean↔Chinese alignment from contextual hidden
      states — but only after a methodological correction: naive mean-centering leaves a near rank-one
      space where cosine is meaningless, and a same-template control shows most of the raw similarity is
      sentence-frame parallelism, not the word. After whitening and that control, the genuine
      <em>word-level</em> alignment <strong>grows with scale</strong> (1.5B → 7B → 14B → 32B), then
      plateaus — the representational echo of the same behavioural story: the grounding emerges with
      capability and then stabilises.
    </p>

    <h2>Relation to the rest of the work</h2>
    <p>
      HanGL is the executed, natural-language companion to two parts of the program. It instantiates the
      <a href="/research/typological-grounding">typological-grounding</a> question — structure vs.
      surface across writing systems — on a phenomenon where the ground truth (Hangul ⟂ Hanja in form,
      ≡ in meaning) is settled in advance, the way the
      <a href="/research/mini-causal-models">sandbox</a> otherwise has to build it by hand. And its
      wrong-Hanja test is the <a href="/research/sc-certification">Paper 1</a> intervention logic applied
      to a surface cue in a real model. The method is the same toolkit — controls, disaggregation,
      bootstrap confidence intervals, an explicit invalid-rate so a weak model's format slips are never
      mistaken for failures of understanding — which is what keeps it from being a description of
      Korean and makes it a grounding measurement.
    </p>

    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-dim)]">
      Status: a pilot, not a finished paper — 60 homophones and 25 low-frequency words; cross-model
      ordering is robust, absolute values may shift after native-speaker review of the draft items. Code,
      data, full results with confidence intervals, and the scaling study are open at
      <a href="https://github.com/xchuan-li/HanGL">github.com/xchuan-li/HanGL</a>.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
